2026-03-26 23:31:55,987 [DEBUG] piper.voice: text=Significant weather discussion issued by the prairie and arctic storm prediction centre of environment canada at 2:00 PM Central Daylight Time thursday march 26 2026.  Alerts In Effect. Yellow blizzard warning for clyde river and naujaat. Yellow cold warning for portions of the kivalliq.  Synoptic Overview. Aloft today, the polar vortex sits near kinngait, Nunavut with a long-wave trough west to an upper low that sits over the gulf of alaska. To the south, a strong zonal flow sits over southern british columbia, the southern prairies, and much of eastern canada. Sat pix show a vigorous shortwave near haida gwaii, one over southwest saskatchewan, one along the eastern coast of the melville peninsula, and another sitting quasi-stationary off the coast of clyde river, Nunavut.  At the surface, a 1042 millibars high sits over northwest alberta with ridging east-southeast across the prairies into northwest ontario and northwest into yukon. To the east, a 1005 millibars occluded low sits west of kinngait, Nunavut. In the north, a warm front drops south from the high arctic into eastern northwest territories before curling east across hudson bay and over northern quebec. In the south, the pacific front drops southeast through british columbia into the british columbia interior then dips southeast into montana.  Discussion.  Alberta, northern Saskatchewan. The next system will begin to move into north-central alberta overnight with snowfall moving into the capital region overnight on friday.  Southern Saskatchewan, Manitoba. The shortwave crossing southern saskatchewan will bring a quick shot of snow to the region. A further 2-4 centimeters will fall across parts of south-central and southeast saskatchewan -- including the trans-canada highway corridor and regina -- then the snow will weaken as it pushes into southern manitoba. No significant accumulations are expected in manitoba overnight. A few flurries will taper off through friday over southern manitoba.  Baffin Island, Kivalliq. The blizzard is continuing in clyde river (cycy) today as the shortwave driving the east baffin barrier jet stalled overnight. Winds continue in the 40 to 50 kilometers per hour range midday and should finally ease later this afternoon as the shortwave slowly pulls east into baffin bay.  In naujaat, heavy ice crystals and moderate winds have resulted in a blizzard for the community. Winds will begin to ease overnight and mid-level moisture will diminish as a cloud shield shifts southwest; this should result in improved visibilities overnight into friday.  Further west, model winds and temperatures continue to struggle with the cold air entrenched over the kivalliq region and have struggled to capture the impact of wind chill over the region. Baker lake (cybk), rankin inlet (cyrt), and chesterfield inlet (cycs) all have. A yellow cold warning in effect and hit wind chill values of -55 or -56 overnight. This will likely occur again tonight, then the cold warnings are expected to end with the next low pressure system heading into the region.  The next band of organized snow for the north will push into the kivalliq region on saturday as a low pressure system drags the warm front draped north-south over the central arctic east into the region. It will bring warmer air into the region along with a couple centimetres of snow that falls along a line from baker lake (cybk) southeast to arviat (cyek) and rankin inlet (cyrt).  Northwest Territories, Kitikmeot, High Arctic. Snow and blowing snow will track into the amundsden gulf on friday with conditions improving by saturday morning., phonemes=[['s', 'ɪ', 'ɡ', 'n', 'ˈ', 'ɪ', 'f', 'ɪ', 'k', 'ə', 'n', 't', ' ', 'w', 'ˈ', 'ɛ', 'ð', 'ɚ', ' ', 'd', 'ɪ', 's', 'k', 'ˈ', 'ʌ', 'ʃ', 'ə', 'n', ' ', 'ˈ', 'ɪ', 'ʃ', 'u', 'ː', 'd', ' ', 'b', 'a', 'ɪ', ' ', 'ð', 'ə', ' ', 'p', 'ɹ', 'ˈ', 'ɛ', 'ɹ', 'i', ' ', 'æ', 'n', 'd', ' ', 'ˈ', 'ɑ', 'ː', 'ɹ', 'k', 't', 'ɪ', 'k', ' ', 's', 't',